    <text>
        <body>
            <div frus:doc-dateTime-max="1973-01-30T23:59:59-05:00"
                frus:doc-dateTime-min="1973-01-30T00:00:00-05:00" n="4"
                subtype="historical-document" type="document" xml:id="d4">
                <head>4. National Security Study Memorandum 167<note n="1" type="source"
                        xml:id="d4fn1">Source: National Archives, <persName corresp="#p_NRM1"
                            >Nixon</persName> Presidential Materials, <gloss target="#t_NSC1"
                            >NSC</gloss> Files, <gloss target="#t_NSC1">NSC</gloss> Institutional
                        Files (<gloss target="#t_H1">H</gloss>–Files), Box <gloss target="#t_H1"
                            >H</gloss>–195, <gloss target="#t_NSSM1">NSSM</gloss> Files, <gloss
                            target="#t_NSSM1">NSSM</gloss> 167. Secret; Sensitive. According to the
                        attached correspondence transmittal sheet, the Vice President, <persName
                            corresp="#p_SB1">Scowcroft</persName>, <persName corresp="#p_OP1"
                            >Odeen</persName>, <persName corresp="#p_KRT1">Kennedy</persName>,
                            <persName corresp="#p_HJH1">Holdridge</persName>, and <persName
                            corresp="#p_NJD1">Negroponte</persName> also received copies.</note>
                </head>
                <opener>
                    <dateline rendition="#right">
                        <placeName>Washington</placeName>, <date calendar="gregorian"
                            when="1973-01-30">January 30, 1973</date>.</dateline>
                </opener>
                <list type="to">
                    <head>TO</head>
                    <item>The Secretary of State</item>
                    <item>The Secretary of Defense</item>
                    <item>The Director of Central Intelligence</item>
                </list>
                <list type="subject">
                    <head>SUBJECT</head>
                    <item>Preparations for the International Conference on Indochina</item>
                </list>
                <p>The President has directed that a study be prepared on an urgent basis concerning
                    the convening of and U.S. participation in the International Conference on
                    Indochina stipulated in Article 19 of the Agreement on Ending the War and
                    Restoring Peace in Vietnam.</p>
                <p>The study should include consideration of: <list>
                        <item>—How the conference should be organized.</item>
                        <item>—The anticipated and preferred duration of the Conference.</item>
                        <item>—The objectives of the Conference and what the U.S. would hope to
                            achieve.</item>
                        <item>—The alternatives for a supervisory relationship with the
                            International Commission of Control and Supervision which could be
                            sought from the Conference.</item>
                        <item>—A possible continuing mechanism for such supervisory responsibilities
                            after the conclusion of the Conference itself.</item>
                        <item>—The relationship of the Conference to the issues of Laos and Cambodia
                            and the existing mechanisms created by the 1954 and the 1962 Geneva
                            Accords.</item>
                        <item>—The possible relationships between the International Conference and
                            other conferences proposed (e.g. <gloss target="#t_ASEAN1">ASEAN</gloss>
                            Conference, the proposed conference of 10 Southeast Asian countries, the
                            conference proposed by the Japanese on post war economic assistance and
                            relationships).</item>
                    </list>
                </p>
                <p>The study should include a proposed game plan and negotiating instructions for
                    the U.S. delegation to the Conference.</p>
                <pb facs="0056" n="15" xml:id="pg_15"/>
                <p>The study should be prepared under the direction of the Chairman of the <gloss
                        target="#t_NSC1">NSC</gloss> Interdepartmental Group for East Asia and be
                    forwarded not later than the opening of business February 2, 1973 for
                    consideration by the <gloss target="#t_NSC1">NSC</gloss> Senior Review
                    Group.</p>
                <closer>
                    <signed>
                        <persName corresp="#p_KHA1">
                            <hi rend="strong">Henry A. Kissinger</hi>
                        </persName>
                    </signed>
                </closer>
            </div>
        </body>
